    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-07-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-07-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="75"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d75">
                <head>75. Letter From <persName corresp="#p_MNH_1">McElroy</persName> to <persName
                        corresp="#p_DJF_1">John Foster Dulles</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d75fn1">Source: Department of Defense position
                        on retaining current strategic concept. Top Secret. 1 p. NARA, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 59, <gloss target="#t_SS_1"
                            >S/S</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Files: Lot 63 D
                        351.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1958-07-18">July 18, 1958</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Foster:</salute>
                </opener>
                <pb facs="d75-1" n="1" type="facsimile" xml:id="d75-1"/>
                <p>I am sending the enclosed Memorandum on Basic National Security Policy (<gloss
                        target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> 5810/1) to the National Security Council
                    today. In view of our recent conversations on this subject I wanted you to have
                    a copy simultaneously.</p>
                <p>You will note that this Department considers that the military section of <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> 5810/1 provides adequately for this segment of
                    our security policy. Our belief is that there is plenty of flexibility in this
                    statement to let us adjust our balance of forces as may be desirable. At the
                    same time, by retaining the present language we do not suggest to any of our
                    allies that there is any retreat in the offing from our past policy of firm
                    resolution to use all required military force for whatever may be the situation
                    that must be met.</p>
                <p>I think it would be highly constructive if State and Defense might have reached a
                    common point of view on this matter before the meeting of the Security Council
                    next Thursday. If you find difficulty in accepting the position we have taken in
                    the attached, perhaps you would phone me and give me your views.</p>
                <p>Sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Neil</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
